  temp_val < 0.3 -> "Very low temperature: repetitive, deterministic output."
  temp_val < 0.8 -> "Low temperature: conservative, sticking to common patterns."
  temp_val < 1.2 -> "Normal temperature: balanced between variety and coherence."
  temp_val < 2.0 -> "High temperature: more creative, less predictable."
  true -> "Very high temperature: approaching random -- nearly uniform sampling."
end}
""")
```

## From Random to Shakespeare

With a random model, the output is gibberish. But the code is exactly the same code that generates real Shakespeare from a trained model. The only difference is the quality of the parameters.

If you were to train the full model (6 layers, 384 dimensions, ~10M parameters) on the Shakespeare dataset for a few thousand iterations on a GPU, you'd see output like:

```
ROMEO:
What shall I swear by? Thou art all my world:
And yet no doubt thou know'st my love is young.
```

The architecture, the loss function, the optimizer, the training loop, and the generation code are all the same. The only things that change are scale (more layers, more dimensions, more data, more compute) and time (more training iterations).

If you have access to a GPU with EXLA's CUDA backend, you can train the full model using `ExNanoGPT.Trainer.train/3` -- the same code we built piece by piece across these notebooks. Even on CPU, you can train a small model overnight and see it start producing recognizable English words, then phrases, then sentences that almost make sense.

## Congratulations!

You've built a complete GPT from scratch in Elixir. Here's everything you implemented across these notebooks:

| Notebook | What you built |
|----------|---------------|
| **00: Language Models** | Tokenization, encoding/decoding, batching |
| **01: Embeddings** | Token and position embeddings -- converting IDs to vectors |
| **02: Layer Norm** | Normalizing activations for stable training |
| **03: Self-Attention** | The core mechanism: letting tokens attend to each other |
| **04: MLP** | Feed-forward layers with GELU activation |
| **05: Transformer Block** | Pre-norm residual connections combining attention and MLP |
| **06: The Full Model** | Stacking blocks with weight-tied input/output embeddings |
| **07: Cross-Entropy Loss** | Measuring how wrong the model's predictions are |
| **08: AdamW Optimizer** | Smartly adjusting parameters with momentum, adaptive LR, and weight decay |
| **09: Training Loop** | Tying it all together: batch → forward → backward → update |
| **10: Sampling** | Generating text with temperature, top-k, and the Gumbel-max trick |

Every one of these components is present in GPT-2, GPT-3, and the models behind ChatGPT and Claude. The difference is scale -- more layers, more heads, more data, more compute -- but the fundamental ideas are the same ones you just built by hand.

## Math Notation: Temperature-Scaled Softmax

Softmax with temperature:

**P(i) = exp(zᵢ / T) / Σⱼ exp(zⱼ / T)**

| Symbol | Meaning | Effect |
|--------|---------|--------|
| `T` | Temperature | Controls distribution sharpness |
| `zᵢ` | Logit for token i | Raw model output |
| `T → 0` | Approaches argmax | Always pick the most likely token |
| `T → ∞` | Approaches uniform | Every token equally likely |
| `T = 1` | Standard softmax | Use the model's distribution as-is |

The complete math notation you've learned across all 11 notebooks:

| Notebook | Symbols |
|----------|---------|
| 00 | Σ (sum), xᵢ (indexing) |
| 01 | W ∈ ℝ^{m×n} (matrix shape), W[i] (row lookup) |
| 02 | μ (mean), σ² (variance), ε (epsilon), γ/β (learnable scale/shift) |
| 03 | Q, K, V (projections), d_k (head dim), softmax, ^T (transpose) |
| 04 | GELU, Φ (Gaussian CDF), erf (error function) |
| 05 | x_{l+1} = x_l + F(x_l) (residual connection) |
| 06 | W_E^T (transposed weight tying) |
| 07 | L (loss), log, P(y\|x) (conditional probability) |
| 08 | α (learning rate), β₁/β₂ (decay rates), ∇ (gradient), θ (parameters) |
| 09 | ∇_θ L (gradient of loss w.r.t. params) |
| 10 | T (temperature), P(i) = exp(zᵢ/T) / Σⱼ exp(zⱼ/T) |

You can now read ML papers. Every symbol above maps directly to code you wrote.

## Key Concepts

| Concept | What it means |
|---------|--------------|
| **Autoregressive generation** | Generating one token at a time, feeding each output back as the next input |
| **Temperature** | Divides logits before softmax; low = deterministic, high = creative |
| **Top-k filtering** | Only consider the k most likely tokens; set the rest to negative infinity |
| **Gumbel-max trick** | Sample from a categorical distribution via `argmax(log_probs + Gumbel_noise)` |
| **Context window** | The model can only see `block_size` tokens at once; crop longer sequences |
| **Greedy decoding** | Always picking the most likely token (equivalent to temperature → 0) |
